If your `Product` class does not have an `setId()` method, it means that the identifier (`id` field) is most likely managed and assigned by the database during the persistence process. In that case, you should remove the line `product.setId("1");` from the test code.

Here's the modified test code without setting the ID:

```java
@Test
void testProductMapping() {
    Product product = new Product();
    product.setName("Product 1");
    product.setDescription("Description 1");
    product.setPrice(9.99);
    // set other attributes

    Product savedProduct = productRepository.save(product);

    assertThat(savedProduct).isNotNull();
    assertThat(savedProduct.getName()).isEqualTo("Product 1");
    assertThat(savedProduct.getDescription()).isEqualTo("Description 1");
    assertThat(savedProduct.getPrice()).isEqualTo(9.99);
    // verify other attributes
}
```

By removing the `setId()` method call and assertion, the test will now only focus on the mapping and persistence of the product attributes (name, description, price, etc.) without explicitly setting the ID.

