@Test
void testProductMapping() {
    Product product = new Product();
    product.setName("Product 1");
    product.setDescription("Description 1");
    product.setPrice(BigDecimal.valueOf(9.99)); // set the price using BigDecimal instead of double
    // set other attributes

    Product savedProduct = productRepository.save(product);

    assertThat(savedProduct).isNotNull();
    assertThat(savedProduct.getName()).isEqualTo("Product 1");
    assertThat(savedProduct.getDescription()).isEqualTo("Description 1");
    assertThat(savedProduct.getPrice()).isEqualTo(BigDecimal.valueOf(9.99));
    // verify other attributes
}
```

By using `BigDecimal.valueOf(9.99)`, we can set the price using a precise decimal representation. Ensure that the `getPrice()` method in the `Product` class returns a `BigDecimal` as well.

This way, the test will correctly handle the precision of the price attribute during mapping and persistence.

Apologies for the incorrect information provided. That line should be modified to instantiate the `ProductRepository` as you mentioned. However, it doesn't need to be `final`. The `final` keyword is used to indicate that the variable cannot be reassigned once it is initialized, which is not necessary in this case. 

To instantiate the `ProductRepository` without using `@Autowired`, you can modify the line to:
```java
private ProductRepository productRepository = new ProductRepositoryImpl(); // Replace with your actual implementation
```
Make sure to replace `ProductRepositoryImpl()` with your actual implementation class.

The modified code would look like this:
```java
